# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: oscillations-resonance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] In physical systems, **damping** is the loss of energy of an oscillating system by dissipation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Damping is an influence within or upon an oscillatory system that has the effect of reducing or preventing its oscillation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Examples of damping include viscous damping in a fluid (see viscous drag), surface friction, radiation, resistance in electronic oscillators, and absorption and scattering of light in optical oscillators.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Damping not based on energy loss can be important in other oscillating systems such as those that occur in biological systems and bikes (ex.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Damping is not to be confused with friction, which is a type of dissipative force acting on a system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Friction can cause or be a factor of damping.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Many systems exhibit oscillatory behavior when they are disturbed from their position of static equilibrium.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] A mass suspended from a spring, for example, might, if pulled and released, bounce up and down.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] On each bounce, the system tends to return to its equilibrium position, but overshoots it.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Sometimes losses (e.g. frictional) damp the system and can cause the oscillations to gradually decay in amplitude towards zero or attenuate.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] The **damping ratio** is a dimensionless measure, amongst other measures, that characterises how damped a system is.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] The behaviour of oscillating systems is often of interest in a diverse range of disciplines that include control engineering, chemical engineering, mechanical engineering, structural engineering, and electrical engineering.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] The physical quantity that is oscillating varies greatly, and could be the swaying of a tall building in the wind, or the speed of an electric motor, but a normalised, or non-dimensionalised approach can be convenient in describing common aspects of behavior.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Depending on the amount of damping present, a system exhibits different oscillatory behaviors and speeds.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] A **damped sine wave** or **damped sinusoid** is a sinusoidal function whose amplitude approaches zero as time increases.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] It corresponds to the *underdamped* case of damped second-order systems, or underdamped second-order differential equations.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Damped sine waves are commonly seen in science and engineering, wherever a harmonic oscillator is losing energy faster than it is being supplied.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] A true sine wave starting at time = 0 begins at the origin (amplitude = 0).
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] A cosine wave begins at its maximum value due to its phase difference from the sine wave.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] A given sinusoidal waveform may be of intermediate phase, having both sine and cosine components.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] The term "damped sine wave" describes all such damped waveforms, whatever their initial phase.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] The most common form of damping, which is usually assumed, is the form found in linear systems.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] This form is exponential damping, in which the outer envelope of the successive peaks is an exponential decay curve.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] That is, when the maximum points of each successive curve are connected, the result resembles an exponential decay function.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] The *damping ratio* is a dimensionless parameter, usually denoted by *ζ* (Greek letter zeta), that characterizes the extent of damping in a second-order ordinary differential equation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] It is particularly important in the study of control theory.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] It is also important in the harmonic oscillator.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] The greater the damping ratio, the more damped a system is.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] The damping ratio is dimensionless, being the ratio of two coefficients of identical units.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] This equation is more general than just the mass-spring-damper system and applies to electrical circuits and to other domains.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] This case is extremely rare in the natural world with the closest examples being cases where friction was purposefully reduced to minimal values.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] is a pair of real values, then the solution is simply a sum of two decaying exponentials with no oscillation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Situations where overdamping is practical tend to have tragic outcomes if overshooting occurs, usually electrical rather than mechanical.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] For example, landing a plane in autopilot: if the system overshoots and releases landing gear too late, the outcome would be a disaster.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] This turns out to be a desirable outcome in many cases where engineering design of a damped oscillator is required (e.g., a door closing mechanism).
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] When a second-order system has $\zeta <1$ (that is, when the system is underdamped), it has two complex conjugate poles that each have a real part of $-\alpha$ ; that is, the decay rate parameter represents the rate of exponential decay of the oscillations.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] A lower damping ratio implies a lower decay rate, and so very underdamped systems oscillate for long times.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] For example, a high quality tuning fork, which has a very low damping ratio, has an oscillation that lasts a long time, decaying very slowly after being struck by a hammer.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] For underdamped vibrations, the damping ratio is also related to the logarithmic decrement $\delta$ .
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] The damping ratio can be found for any two peaks, even if they are not adjacent.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] where *x*0 and *x*1 are amplitudes of any two successive peaks.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] where $x_{1}$ , $x_{3}$ are amplitudes of two successive positive peaks and $x_{2}$ , $x_{4}$ are amplitudes of two successive negative peaks.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] In control theory, overshoot refers to an output exceeding its final, steady-state value.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] For a step input, the **percentage overshoot** (PO) is the maximum value minus the step value divided by the step value.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] In the case of the unit step, the *overshoot* is just the maximum value of the step response minus one.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] When an object is falling through the air, the only force opposing its freefall is air resistance.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] An object falling through water or oil would slow down at a greater rate, until eventually reaching a steady-state velocity as the drag force comes into equilibrium with the force from gravity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] This is the concept of viscous drag, which for example is applied in automatic doors or anti-slam doors.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Electrical systems that operate with alternating current (AC) use resistors to damp LC resonant circuits.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Kinetic energy that causes oscillations is dissipated as heat by electric eddy currents which are induced by passing through a magnet's poles, either by a coil or aluminum plate.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Eddy currents are a key component of electromagnetic induction where they set up a magnetic flux directly opposing the oscillating movement, creating a resistive force.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] In other words, the resistance caused by magnetic forces slows a system down.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] An example of this concept being applied is the brakes on roller coasters.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Magnetorheological dampers (MR Dampers) use Magnetorheological fluid, which changes viscosity when subjected to a magnetic field.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] In this case, Magnetorheological damping may be considered an interdisciplinary form of damping with both viscous and magnetic damping mechanisms.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Materials have varying degrees of internal damping properties due to microstructural mechanisms within them.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] This property is sometimes known as damping capacity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] In metals, this arises due to movements of dislocations, as demonstrated nicely in this video: metals, as well as ceramics and glass, are known for having very light material damping.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] By contrast, polymers have a much higher material damping that arises from the energy loss required to contiually break and reform the Van der Waals forces between polymer chains.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] The cross-linking in thermoset plastics causes less movement of the polymer chains and so the damping is less.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] This is because many microstructural processes that contribute to material damping are not well modelled by viscous damping, and so the damping ratio varies with frequency.
[src:oscillations-resonance/damping] Adding the frequency ratio as a factor typically makes the loss factor constant over a wide frequency range.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] In classical mechanics, a **harmonic oscillator** is a system that, when displaced from its equilibrium position, experiences a restoring force *F* proportional to the displacement *x*: ${\vec {F}}=-k{\vec {x}},$ where *k* is a positive constant.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The harmonic oscillator model is important in physics, because any mass subject to a force in stable equilibrium acts as a harmonic oscillator for small vibrations.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Harmonic oscillators occur widely in nature and are exploited in many manmade devices, such as clocks and radio circuits.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] If *F* is the only force acting on the system, the system is called a **simple harmonic oscillator**, and it undergoes simple harmonic motion: sinusoidal oscillations about the equilibrium point, with a constant amplitude and a constant frequency (which does not depend on the amplitude).
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] If a frictional force (damping) proportional to the velocity is also present, the harmonic oscillator is described as a **damped oscillator**.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The boundary solution between an underdamped oscillator and an overdamped oscillator occurs at a particular value of the friction coefficient and is called critically damped.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] If an external time-dependent force is present, the harmonic oscillator is described as a *driven oscillator*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Mechanical examples include pendulums (with small angles of displacement), masses connected to springs, and acoustical systems.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Other analogous systems include electrical harmonic oscillators such as RLC circuits.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] They are the source of virtually all sinusoidal vibrations and waves.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] A simple harmonic oscillator is an oscillator that is neither driven nor damped.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] It consists of a mass m , which experiences a single force F , which pulls the mass in the direction of the point $x=0$ and depends only on the position x of the mass and a constant k .
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The motion is periodic, repeating itself in a sinusoidal fashion with constant amplitude *A*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] In addition to its amplitude, the motion of a simple harmonic oscillator is characterized by its period $T=2\pi /\omega$ , the time for a single oscillation or its frequency $f=1/T$ , the number of cycles per unit time.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The position at a given time *t* also depends on the phase $\varphi$ , which determines the starting point on the sine wave.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The period and frequency are determined by the size of the mass *m* and the force constant *k*, while the amplitude and phase are determined by the starting position and velocity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The velocity and acceleration of a simple harmonic oscillator oscillate with the same frequency as the position, but with shifted phases.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The velocity is maximal for zero displacement, while the acceleration is in the direction opposite to the displacement.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] In real oscillators, friction, or damping, slows the motion of the system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Due to frictional force, the velocity decreases in proportion to the acting frictional force.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] While in a simple undriven harmonic oscillator the only force acting on the mass is the restoring force, in a damped harmonic oscillator there is in addition a frictional force which is always in a direction to oppose the motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] In many vibrating systems the frictional force *F*f can be modeled as being proportional to the velocity *v* of the object: *F*f = −*cv*, where *c* is called the *viscous damping coefficient*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The value of the damping ratio *ζ* critically determines the behavior of the system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Driven harmonic oscillators (also called forced harmonic oscillators) are damped oscillators further affected by an externally applied force *F*(*t*).
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] and which can be expressed as damped sinusoidal oscillations: $z(t)=Ae^{-\zeta \omega _{0}t}\sin \left({\sqrt {1-\zeta ^{2}}}\omega _{0}t+\varphi \right),$ in the case where *ζ* ≤ 1.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The amplitude *A* and phase *φ* determine the behavior needed to match the initial conditions.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The time an oscillator needs to adapt to changed external conditions is of the order *τ* = 1/(*ζω*0).
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] In physics, the adaptation is called relaxation, and *τ* is called the relaxation time.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] In electrical engineering, a multiple of *τ* is called the *settling time*, i.e. the time necessary to ensure the signal is within a fixed departure from final value, typically within 10%.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The term *overshoot* refers to the extent the response maximum exceeds final value, and *undershoot* refers to the extent the response falls below final value for times following the response maximum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] This type of system appears in AC-driven RLC circuits (resistor–inductor–capacitor) and driven spring systems having internal mechanical resistance or external air resistance.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] is the phase of the oscillation relative to the driving force.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The phase value is usually taken to be between −180° and 0 (that is, it represents a phase lag, for both positive and negative values of the arctan argument).
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] For a particular driving frequency called the resonance, or resonant frequency ${\textstyle \omega _{r}=\omega _{0}{\sqrt {1-2\zeta ^{2}}}}$ , the amplitude (for a given $F_{0}$ ) is maximal.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] This resonance effect only occurs when $\zeta <1/{\sqrt {2}}$ , i.e. for significantly underdamped systems.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] For strongly underdamped systems the value of the amplitude can become quite large near the resonant frequency.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The transient solutions are the same as the unforced ( $F_{0}=0$ ) damped harmonic oscillator and represent the system's response to other events that occurred previously.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] A parametric oscillator is a driven harmonic oscillator in which the drive energy is provided by varying the parameters of the oscillator, such as the damping or restoring force.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] A familiar example of parametric oscillation is "pumping" on a playground swing.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The varying of the parameters drives the system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Examples of parameters that may be varied are its resonance frequency $\omega$ and damping $\beta$ .
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Parametric oscillators are used in many applications.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The classical varactor parametric oscillator oscillates when the diode's capacitance is varied periodically.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The circuit that varies the diode's capacitance is called the "pump" or "driver".
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] In microwave electronics, waveguide/YAG based parametric oscillators operate in the same fashion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The designer varies a parameter periodically to induce oscillations.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Parametric oscillators have been developed as low-noise amplifiers, especially in the radio and microwave frequency range.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Thermal noise is minimal, since a reactance (not a resistance) is varied.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Another common use is frequency conversion, e.g., conversion from audio to radio frequencies.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] For example, the Optical parametric oscillator converts an input laser wave into two output waves of lower frequency ( $\omega _{s},\omega _{i}$ ).
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Parametric resonance occurs in a mechanical system when a system is parametrically excited and oscillates at one of its resonant frequencies.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Parametric excitation differs from forcing, since the action appears as a time varying modification on a system parameter.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] This effect is different from regular resonance because it exhibits the instability phenomenon.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The equation ${\frac {\mathrm {d} ^{2}q}{\mathrm {d} \tau ^{2}}}+2\zeta {\frac {\mathrm {d} q}{\mathrm {d} \tau }}+q=0$ is known as the **universal oscillator equation**, since all second-order linear oscillatory systems can be reduced to this form.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] This is done through nondimensionalization.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The solution to this differential equation contains two parts: the "transient" and the "steady-state".
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The transient solution is independent of the forcing function.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Compare this result with the theory section on resonance, as well as the "magnitude part" of the RLC circuit.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] This amplitude function is particularly important in the analysis and understanding of the frequency response of second-order systems.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] This phase function is particularly important in the analysis and understanding of the frequency response of second-order systems.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Harmonic oscillators occurring in a number of areas of engineering are equivalent in the sense that their mathematical models are identical (see universal oscillator equation above).
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Below is a table showing analogous quantities in four harmonic oscillator systems in mechanics and electronics.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] If analogous parameters on the same line in the table are given numerically equal values, the behavior of the oscillators – their output waveform, resonant frequency, damping factor, etc. – are the same.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The problem of the simple harmonic oscillator occurs frequently in physics, because a mass at equilibrium under the influence of any conservative force, in the limit of small motions, behaves as a simple harmonic oscillator.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] A conservative force is one that is associated with a potential energy.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Given an arbitrary potential-energy function $V(x)$ , one can do a Taylor expansion in terms of x around an energy minimum ( $x=x_{0}$ ) to model the behavior of small perturbations from equilibrium.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Thus, given an arbitrary potential-energy function $V(x)$ with a non-vanishing second derivative, one can use the solution to the simple harmonic oscillator to provide an approximate solution for small perturbations around the equilibrium point.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The general solution to this differential equation is $\theta (t)=A\cos \left({\sqrt {\frac {g}{l}}}t+\varphi \right),$ where A and $\varphi$ are constants that depend on the initial conditions.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Using as initial conditions $\theta (0)=\theta _{0}$ and ${\dot {\theta }}(0)=0$ , the solution is given by $\theta (t)=\theta _{0}\cos \left({\sqrt {\frac {g}{l}}}t\right),$ where $\theta _{0}$ is the largest angle attained by the pendulum (that is, $\theta _{0}$ is the amplitude of the pendulum).
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The period, the time for one complete oscillation, is given by the expression $\tau =2\pi {\sqrt {\frac {l}{g}}}={\frac {2\pi }{\omega }},$ which is a good approximation of the actual period when $\theta _{0}$ is small.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Notice that in this approximation the period $\tau$ is independent of the amplitude $\theta _{0}$ .
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] In the above equation, $\omega$ represents the angular frequency.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] When a spring is stretched or compressed by a mass, the spring develops a restoring force.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Hooke's law gives the relationship of the force exerted by the spring when the spring is compressed or stretched a certain length: $F(t)=-kx(t),$ where *F* is the force, *k* is the spring constant, and *x* is the displacement of the mass with respect to the equilibrium position.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] The minus sign in the equation indicates that the force exerted by the spring always acts in a direction that is opposite to the displacement (i.e. the force always acts towards the zero position), and so prevents the mass from flying off to infinity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] By using either force balance or an energy method, it can be readily shown that the motion of this system is given by the following differential equation: $F(t)=-kx(t)=m{\frac {\mathrm {d} ^{2}}{\mathrm {d} t^{2}}}x(t)=ma,$ the latter being Newton's second law of motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] Given an ideal massless spring, m is the mass on the end of the spring.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] If the spring itself has mass, its effective mass must be included in m .
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] In terms of energy, all systems have two types of energy: potential energy and kinetic energy.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] When a spring is stretched or compressed, it stores elastic potential energy, which is then transferred into kinetic energy.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] When the spring is stretched or compressed, kinetic energy of the mass gets converted into potential energy of the spring.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] By conservation of energy, assuming the datum is defined at the equilibrium position, when the spring reaches its maximal potential energy, the kinetic energy of the mass is zero.
[src:oscillations-resonance/harmonic-oscillator] When the spring is released, it tries to return to equilibrium, and all its potential energy converts to kinetic energy of the mass.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] A **normal mode** of a dynamical system is a pattern of motion in which all parts of the system move sinusoidally with the same frequency and with a fixed phase relation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The free motion described by the normal modes takes place at fixed frequencies.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] These fixed frequencies of the normal modes of a system are known as its natural frequencies or resonant frequencies.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] A physical object, such as a building, bridge, or molecule, has a set of normal modes and their natural frequencies that depend on its structure, materials and boundary conditions.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The most general motion of a linear system is a superposition of its normal modes.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The modes are "normal" in the sense that they move independently.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] An excitation of one mode will never cause excitation of a different mode.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In mathematical terms, normal modes are orthogonal to each other.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In the wave theory of physics and engineering, a **mode** in a dynamical system is a standing wave state of excitation, in which all the components of the system will be affected sinusoidally at a fixed frequency associated with that mode.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Because no real system can perfectly fit under the standing wave framework, the *mode* concept is taken as a general characterization of specific states of oscillation, thus treating the dynamic system in a *linear* fashion, in which linear superposition of states can be performed.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The concept of normal modes also finds application in other dynamical systems, such as optics, quantum mechanics, atmospheric dynamics and molecular dynamics.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Most dynamical systems can be excited in several modes, possibly simultaneously.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Each mode is characterized by one or several frequencies, according to the modal variable field.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] For example, a vibrating rope in 2D space is defined by a single-frequency (1D axial displacement), but a vibrating rope in 3D space is defined by two frequencies (2D axial displacement).
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] For a given amplitude on the modal variable, each mode will store a specific amount of energy because of the sinusoidal excitation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] A mode of vibration is characterized by a modal frequency and a mode shape.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] It is numbered according to the number of half waves in the vibration.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] For example, if a vibrating beam with both ends pinned displayed a mode shape of half of a sine wave (one peak on the vibrating beam) it would be vibrating in mode 1.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] If it had a full sine wave (one peak and one trough) it would be vibrating in mode 2.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In a system with two or more dimensions, such as the pictured disk, each dimension is given a mode number.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Using polar coordinates, we have a radial coordinate and an angular coordinate.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] If one measured from the center outward along the radial coordinate one would encounter a full wave, so the mode number in the radial direction is 2.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The other direction is trickier, because only half of the disk is considered due to the anti-symmetric (also called skew-symmetry) nature of a disk's vibration in the angular direction.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Thus, measuring 180° along the angular direction you would encounter a half wave, so the mode number in the angular direction is 1.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] So the mode number of the system is 2–1 or 1–2, depending on which coordinate is considered the "first" and which is considered the "second" coordinate (so it is important to always indicate which mode number matches with each coordinate direction).
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In linear systems each mode is entirely independent of all other modes.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In general all modes have different frequencies (with lower modes having lower frequencies) and different mode shapes.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In a one-dimensional system at a given mode the vibration will have nodes, or places where the displacement is always zero.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] These nodes correspond to points in the mode shape where the mode shape is zero.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Since the vibration of a system is given by the mode shape multiplied by a time function, the displacement of the node points remain zero at all times.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] When expanded to a two dimensional system, these nodes become lines where the displacement is always zero.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] If you watch the animation above you will see two circles (one about halfway between the edge and center, and the other on the edge itself) and a straight line bisecting the disk, where the displacement is close to zero.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In an idealized system these lines equal zero exactly, as shown to the right.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Consider two equal bodies (not affected by gravity), each of mass m, attached to three springs, each with spring constant k.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] where the edge points are fixed and cannot move.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Let *x*1(*t*) denote the horizontal displacement of the left mass, and *x*2(*t*) denote the displacement of the right mass.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] If the matrix on the left is invertible, the unique solution is the trivial solution (*A*1, *A*2) = (*x*1, *x*2) = (0, 0).
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The non trivial solutions are to be found for those values of ω whereby the matrix on the left is singular; i.e. is not invertible.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Substituting *ω*1 into the matrix and solving for (*A*1, *A*2), yields (1, 1).
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Which corresponds to both masses moving in the same direction at the same time.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] This corresponds to the masses moving in the opposite directions, while the center of mass remains stationary.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The general solution is a superposition of the **normal modes** where *c*1, *c*2, *φ*1, and *φ*2 are determined by the initial conditions of the problem.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The process demonstrated here can be generalized and formulated using the formalism of Lagrangian mechanics or Hamiltonian mechanics.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] A standing wave is a continuous form of normal mode.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In a standing wave, all the space elements (i.e.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] (*x*, *y*, *z*) coordinates) are oscillating in the same frequency and in phase (reaching the equilibrium point together), but each has a different amplitude.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] where *f*(*x*, *y*, *z*) represents the dependence of amplitude on location and the cosine/sine are the oscillations in time.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Physically, standing waves are formed by the interference (superposition) of waves and their reflections (although one may also say the opposite; that a moving wave is a superposition of standing waves).
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The geometric shape of the medium determines what would be the interference pattern, thus determines the *f*(*x*, *y*, *z*) form of the standing wave.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] This space-dependence is called a **normal mode**.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Usually, for problems with continuous dependence on (*x*, *y*, *z*) there is no single or finite number of normal modes, but there are infinitely many normal modes.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] If the problem is bounded (i.e. it is defined on a finite section of space) there are countably many normal modes (usually numbered *n* = 1, 2, 3, ...).
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] If the problem is not bounded, there is a continuous spectrum of normal modes.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In any solid at any temperature, the primary particles (e.g. atoms or molecules) are not stationary, but rather vibrate about mean positions.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In insulators the capacity of the solid to store thermal energy is due almost entirely to these vibrations.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Many physical properties of the solid (e.g. modulus of elasticity) can be predicted given knowledge of the frequencies with which the particles vibrate.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The simplest assumption (by Einstein) is that all the particles oscillate about their mean positions with the same natural frequency ν.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] This is equivalent to the assumption that all atoms vibrate independently with a frequency ν.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Einstein also assumed that the allowed energy states of these oscillations are harmonics, or integral multiples of hν.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The spectrum of waveforms can be described mathematically using a Fourier series of sinusoidal density fluctuations (or thermal phonons).
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Debye subsequently recognized that each oscillator is intimately coupled to its neighboring oscillators at all times.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Thus, by replacing Einstein's identical uncoupled oscillators with the same number of coupled oscillators, Debye correlated the elastic vibrations of a one-dimensional solid with the number of mathematically special modes of vibration of a stretched string (see figure).
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The pure tone of lowest pitch or frequency is referred to as the fundamental and the multiples of that frequency are called its harmonic overtones.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] He assigned to one of the oscillators the frequency of the fundamental vibration of the whole block of solid.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] He assigned to the remaining oscillators the frequencies of the harmonics of that fundamental, with the highest of all these frequencies being limited by the motion of the smallest primary unit.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The normal modes of vibration of a crystal are in general superpositions of many overtones, each with an appropriate amplitude and phase.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Longer wavelength (low frequency) phonons are exactly those acoustical vibrations which are considered in the theory of sound.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Both longitudinal and transverse waves can be propagated through a solid, while, in general, only longitudinal waves are supported by fluids.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In the longitudinal mode, the displacement of particles from their positions of equilibrium coincides with the propagation direction of the wave.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Mechanical longitudinal waves have been also referred to as **compression waves**.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] For transverse modes, individual particles move perpendicular to the propagation of the wave.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The term (1/2)*hν* represents the "zero-point energy", or the energy which an oscillator will have at absolute zero.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] In order to calculate the internal energy and the specific heat, we must know the number of normal vibrational modes a frequency between the values ν and *ν* + *dν*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The integration is performed over all frequencies of the crystal.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Bound states in quantum mechanics are analogous to modes.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The waves in quantum systems are oscillations in probability amplitude rather than material displacement.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The frequency of oscillation, f, relates to the mode energy by *E* = *hf* where h is the Planck constant.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Thus a system like an atom consists of a linear combination of modes of definite energy.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] These energies are characteristic of the particular atom.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The (complex) square of the probability amplitude at a point in space gives the probability of measuring an electron at that location.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The spatial distribution of this probability is characteristic of the atom.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Normal modes are generated in the Earth from long wavelength seismic waves from large earthquakes interfering to form standing waves.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] For an elastic, isotropic, homogeneous sphere, spheroidal, toroidal and radial (or breathing) modes arise.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Spheroidal modes only involve P and SV waves (like Rayleigh waves) and depend on overtone number n and angular order l but have degeneracy of azimuthal order m.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Increasing l concentrates fundamental branch closer to surface and at large l this tends to Rayleigh waves.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Toroidal modes only involve SH waves (like Love waves) and do not exist in fluid outer core.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Radial modes are just a subset of spheroidal modes with *l* = 0.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] The degeneracy does not exist on Earth as it is broken by rotation, ellipticity and 3D heterogeneous velocity and density structure.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] It may be assumed that each mode can be isolated, the self-coupling approximation, or that many modes close in frequency resonate, the cross-coupling approximation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Self-coupling will solely change the phase velocity and not the number of waves around a great circle, resulting in a stretching or shrinking of standing wave pattern.
[src:oscillations-resonance/normal-mode] Modal cross-coupling occurs due to the rotation of the Earth, from aspherical elastic structure, or due to Earth's ellipticity and leads to a mixing of fundamental spheroidal and toroidal modes.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The term *vibration* is precisely used to describe a mechanical oscillation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Oscillation, especially rapid oscillation, may be an undesirable phenomenon in process control and control theory (e.g. in sliding mode control), where the aim is convergence to stable state.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] In these cases it is called chattering or flapping, as in valve chatter, and route flapping.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The simplest mechanical oscillating system is a weight attached to a linear spring subject to only weight and tension.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Such a system may be approximated on an air table or ice surface.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The system is in an equilibrium state when the spring is static.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] If the system is displaced from the equilibrium, there is a net *restoring force* on the mass, tending to bring it back to equilibrium.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] However, in moving the mass back to the equilibrium position, it has acquired momentum which keeps it moving beyond that position, establishing a new restoring force in the opposite sense.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] If a constant force such as gravity is added to the system, the point of equilibrium is shifted.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The time taken for an oscillation to occur is often referred to as the oscillatory *period*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The systems where the restoring force on a body is directly proportional to its displacement, such as the dynamics of the spring-mass system, are described mathematically by the simple harmonic oscillator and the regular periodic motion is known as simple harmonic motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] In the spring-mass system, oscillations occur because, at the static equilibrium displacement, the mass has kinetic energy which is converted into potential energy stored in the spring at the extremes of its path.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The spring-mass system illustrates some common features of oscillation, namely the existence of an equilibrium and the presence of a restoring force which grows stronger the further the system deviates from equilibrium.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] where ω is the frequency of the oscillation, A is the amplitude, and δ is the phase shift of the function.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] These are determined by the initial conditions of the system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Because cosine oscillates between 1 and −1 infinitely, our spring-mass system would oscillate between the positive and negative amplitude forever without friction.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] In two or three dimensions, harmonic oscillators behave similarly to one dimension.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] With anisotropic oscillators, different directions have different constants of restoring forces.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The solution is similar to isotropic oscillators, but there is a different frequency in each direction.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Varying the frequencies relative to each other can produce interesting results.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] For example, if the frequency in one direction is twice that of another, a figure eight pattern is produced.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] If the ratio of frequencies is irrational, the motion is quasiperiodic.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] This motion is periodic on each axis, but is not periodic with respect to r, and will never repeat.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] All real-world oscillator systems are thermodynamically irreversible.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] This means there are dissipative processes such as friction or electrical resistance which continually convert some of the energy stored in the oscillator into heat in the environment.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Thus, oscillations tend to decay with time unless there is some net source of energy into the system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The simplest description of this decay process can be illustrated by oscillation decay of the harmonic oscillator.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Damped oscillators are created when a resistive force is introduced, which is dependent on the first derivative of the position, or in this case velocity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The differential equation created by Newton's second law adds in this resistive force with an arbitrary constant b.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The exponential term outside of the parenthesis is the decay function and β is the damping coefficient.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] There are 3 categories of damped oscillators: under-damped, where *β* < *ω*0; over-damped, where *β* > *ω*0; and critically damped, where *β* = *ω*0.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] In addition, an oscillating system may be subject to some external force, as when an AC circuit is connected to an outside power source.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] In this case the oscillation is said to be *driven*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The second term of *x*(*t*) is the transient solution to the differential equation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The transient solution can be found by using the initial conditions of the system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Some systems can be excited by energy transfer from the environment.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] This transfer typically occurs where systems are embedded in some fluid flow.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] At sufficiently large displacements, the stiffness of the wing dominates to provide the restoring force that enables an oscillation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Resonance occurs in a damped driven oscillator when ω = ω0, that is, when the driving frequency is equal to the natural frequency of the system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] When this occurs, the denominator of the amplitude is minimized, which maximizes the amplitude of the oscillations.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The harmonic oscillator and the systems it models have a single degree of freedom.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] More complicated systems have more degrees of freedom, for example, two masses and three springs (each mass being attached to fixed points and to each other).
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] In such cases, the behavior of each variable influences that of the others.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] This leads to a *coupling* of the oscillations of the individual degrees of freedom.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] For example, two pendulum clocks (of identical frequency) mounted on a common wall will tend to synchronise.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] This phenomenon was first observed by Christiaan Huygens in 1665.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The apparent motions of the compound oscillations typically appears very complicated but a more economic, computationally simpler and conceptually deeper description is given by resolving the motion into normal modes.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The simplest form of coupled oscillators is a 3 spring, 2 mass system, where masses and spring constants are the same.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Depending on the starting point of the masses, this system has 2 possible frequencies (or a combination of the two).
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] If the masses are started with their displacements in the same direction, the frequency is that of a single mass system, because the middle spring is never extended.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] If the two masses are started in opposite directions, the second, faster frequency is the frequency of the system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] More special cases are the coupled oscillators where energy alternates between two forms of oscillation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Well-known is the Wilberforce pendulum, where the oscillation alternates between the elongation of a vertical spring and the rotation of an object at the end of that spring.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Coupled oscillators are a common description of two related, but different phenomena.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] One case is where both oscillations affect each other mutually, which usually leads to the occurrence of a single, entrained oscillation state, where both oscillate with a *compromise frequency*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Another case is where one external oscillation affects an internal oscillation, but is not affected by this.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] In this case the regions of synchronization, known as Arnold Tongues, can lead to highly complex phenomena as for instance chaotic dynamics.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] In physics, a system with a set of conservative forces and an equilibrium point can be approximated as a harmonic oscillator near equilibrium.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The system will undergo oscillations near the equilibrium point.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] This approximation can be better understood by looking at the potential curve of the system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] By thinking of the potential curve as a hill, in which, if one placed a ball anywhere on the curve, the ball would roll down with the slope of the potential curve.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] By thinking of the potential in this way, one will see that at any local minimum there is a "well" in which the ball would roll back and forth (oscillate) between $r_{\text{min}}$ and $r_{\text{max}}$ .
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] This approximation is also useful for thinking of Kepler orbits.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] As the number of degrees of freedom becomes arbitrarily large, a system approaches continuity; examples include a string or the surface of a body of water.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] Such systems have (in the classical limit) an infinite number of normal modes and their oscillations occur in the form of waves that can characteristically propagate.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] The mathematics of oscillation deals with the quantification of the amount that a sequence or function tends to move between extremes.
[src:oscillations-resonance/oscillation] There are several related notions: oscillation of a sequence of real numbers, oscillation of a real-valued function at a point, and oscillation of a function on an interval (or open set).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] A **pendulum** is a mechanical device consisting of a weight suspended from a pivot so that it can swing freely.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] When a pendulum is displaced sideways from its resting mechanical equilibrium position, it is subject to a restoring force due to gravity, which will accelerate it back toward the equilibrium position.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] When released, the restoring force acting on the pendulum's mass causes it to oscillate about the equilibrium position, swinging back and forth.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The time for one complete cycle, a left swing and a right swing, or frequency, is commonly known as its "period".
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The period depends both on the length of the pendulum and, somewhat, on the amplitude (the width of the pendulum's swing).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The SI unit of the period of a pendulum is the second (s).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The regular motion of a pendulum lends itself to timekeeping.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The pendulum clock was invented by Christiaan Huygens in 1656.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] It became the world's standard manner of timekeeping, used in homes and offices for 270 years.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The Shortt-Synchronome clock achieved accuracy of about one second per year before it was superseded as a time standard by the quartz clock in the 1930s.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Pendulums are also used in scientific instruments such as accelerometers and seismometers.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Historically, pendulums were used as gravimeters to measure the acceleration of gravity in geo-physical surveys, and as a standard of length.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The word *pendulum* is Neo-Latin, from the Latin *pendulus*, meaning 'hanging'.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The *simple gravity pendulum* is an idealized mathematical model of a pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This is a weight (or bob) on the end of a massless cord suspended from a pivot, without friction.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] When given an initial push, it will swing back and forth at a constant amplitude.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Real pendulums are subject to friction and air drag, so the amplitude of their swings declines.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The period of swing of a simple gravity pendulum depends on its length, the local strength of gravity, and to a small extent on the maximum angle that the pendulum swings away from vertical, *θ*0, called the amplitude.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] It is independent of the mass of the bob.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] where L is the length of the pendulum and g is the local acceleration of gravity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] For small swings the period of swing is approximately the same for different size swings: that is, *the period is independent of amplitude*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This property, called isochronism, is the reason pendulums are so useful for timekeeping.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Successive swings of the pendulum, even if changing in amplitude, take the same amount of time.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] For larger amplitudes, the period increases gradually with amplitude so it is longer than given by equation (1).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] For example, at an amplitude of *θ*0 = 0.4 radians (23°) it is 1% larger than given by (1).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The period increases asymptotically (to infinity) as *θ*0 approaches π radians (180°), because the value *θ*0 = π is an unstable equilibrium point for the pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The difference between this true period and the period for small swings (1) above is called the *circular error*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In the case of a typical grandfather clock whose pendulum has a swing of 6° and thus an amplitude of 3° (0.05 radians), the difference between the true period and the small angle approximation (1) amounts to about 15 seconds per day.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] For small swings the pendulum approximates a harmonic oscillator, and its motion as a function of time, *t*, is approximately simple harmonic motion: $\theta (t)=\theta _{0}\cos \left({\frac {2\pi }{T}}\,t+\varphi \right)$ where $\varphi$ is a constant value, dependent on initial conditions.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] For real pendulums, the period varies slightly with factors such as the buoyancy and viscous resistance of the air, the mass of the string or rod, the size and shape of the bob and how it is attached to the string, and flexibility and stretching of the string.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In precision applications, corrections for these factors may need to be applied to eq.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] A damped, driven pendulum is a chaotic system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Any swinging rigid body free to rotate about a fixed horizontal axis is called a **compound pendulum** or **physical pendulum**.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] A compound pendulum has the same period as a simple gravity pendulum of length $\ell ^{\mathrm {eq} }$ , called the *equivalent length* or *radius of oscillation*, equal to the distance from the pivot to a point called the *center of oscillation*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This point is located under the center of mass of the pendulum, at a distance which depends on the mass distribution of the pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] If most of the mass is concentrated in a relatively small bob compared to the pendulum length, the center of oscillation is close to the center of mass.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] where $I_{O}$ is the moment of inertia of the pendulum about the pivot point O , m is the total mass of the pendulum, and $r_{\mathrm {CM} }$ is the distance between the pivot point and the center of mass.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Substituting this expression in (1) above, the period T of a compound pendulum is given by $T=2\pi {\sqrt {\frac {I_{O}}{mgr_{\mathrm {CM} }}}}$ for sufficiently small oscillations.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] For example, a rigid uniform rod of length $\ell$ pivoted about one end has moment of inertia ${\textstyle I_{O}={\frac {1}{3}}m\ell ^{2}}$ .
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The center of mass is located at the center of the rod, so ${\textstyle r_{\mathrm {CM} }={\frac {1}{2}}\ell }$ Substituting these values into the above equation gives ${\textstyle T=2\pi {\sqrt {\frac {{\frac {2}{3}}\ell }{g}}}}$ .
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This shows that a rigid rod pendulum has the same period as a simple pendulum of two-thirds its length.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Christiaan Huygens proved in 1673 that the pivot point and the center of oscillation are interchangeable.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This means if any pendulum is turned upside down and swung from a pivot located at its previous center of oscillation, it will have the same period as before and the new center of oscillation will be at the old pivot point.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In 1817 Henry Kater used this idea to produce a type of reversible pendulum, now known as a Kater pendulum, for improved measurements of the acceleration due to gravity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In physics and mathematics, in the area of dynamical systems, a double pendulum, also known as a chaotic pendulum, is a pendulum with another pendulum attached to its end, forming a simple physical system that exhibits rich dynamic behavior with a strong sensitivity to initial conditions.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The motion of a double pendulum is governed by a set of coupled ordinary differential equations and is chaotic.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] One of the earliest known uses of a pendulum was a 1st-century seismometer device of Han dynasty Chinese scientist Zhang Heng.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Its function was to sway and activate one of a series of levers after being disturbed by the tremor of an earthquake far away.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Released by a lever, a small ball would fall out of the urn-shaped device into one of eight metal toads' mouths below, at the eight points of the compass, signifying the direction the earthquake was located.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Many sources claim that the 10th-century Egyptian astronomer Ibn Yunus used a pendulum for time measurement, but this was an error that originated in 1684 with the British historian Edward Bernard.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] During the Renaissance, large hand-pumped pendulums were used as sources of power for manual reciprocating machines such as saws, bellows, and pumps.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Italian scientist Galileo Galilei was the first to study the properties of pendulums, beginning around 1602.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The first recorded interest in pendulums made by Galileo was around 1588 in his posthumously published notes titled *On Motion*, in which he noted that heavier objects would continue to oscillate for a greater amount of time than lighter objects.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The earliest extant report of his experimental research is contained in a letter to Guido Ubaldo dal Monte, from Padua, dated November 29, 1602.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] His biographer and student, Vincenzo Viviani, claimed his interest had been sparked around 1582 by the swinging motion of a chandelier in Pisa Cathedral.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Galileo discovered the crucial property that makes pendulums useful as timekeepers, called isochronism; the period of the pendulum is approximately independent of the amplitude or width of the swing.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] He also found that the period is independent of the mass of the bob, and proportional to the square root of the length of the pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] He first employed freeswinging pendulums in simple timing applications.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Santorio Santori in 1602 invented a device which measured a patient's pulse by the length of a pendulum; the *pulsilogium*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In 1641 Galileo dictated to his son Vincenzo a design for a mechanism to keep a pendulum swinging, which has been described as the first pendulum clock; Vincenzo began construction, but had not completed it when he died in 1649.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In 1656 the Dutch scientist Christiaan Huygens built the first pendulum clock.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This was a great improvement over existing mechanical clocks; their best accuracy was improved from around 15 minutes deviation a day to around 15 seconds a day.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Pendulums spread over Europe as existing clocks were retrofitted with them.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The English scientist Robert Hooke studied the conical pendulum around 1666, consisting of a pendulum that is free to swing in two dimensions, with the bob rotating in a circle or ellipse.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] He used the motions of this device as a model to analyze the orbital motions of the planets.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Hooke suggested to Isaac Newton in 1679 that the components of orbital motion consisted of inertial motion along a tangent direction plus an attractive motion in the radial direction.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This played a part in Newton's formulation of the law of universal gravitation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Robert Hooke was also responsible for suggesting as early as 1666 that the pendulum could be used to measure the force of gravity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] During his expedition to Cayenne, French Guiana in 1671, Jean Richer found that a pendulum clock was 2+1⁄2 minutes per day slower at Cayenne than at Paris.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] From this he deduced that the force of gravity was lower at Cayenne.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In 1687, Isaac Newton in *Principia Mathematica* showed that this was because the Earth was not a true sphere but slightly oblate (flattened at the poles) from the effect of centrifugal force due to its rotation, causing gravity to increase with latitude.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Portable pendulums began to be taken on voyages to distant lands, as precision gravimeters to measure the acceleration of gravity at different points on Earth, eventually resulting in accurate models of the shape of the Earth.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In 1673, 17 years after he invented the pendulum clock, Christiaan Huygens published his theory of the pendulum, *Horologium Oscillatorium sive de motu pendulorum*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Marin Mersenne and René Descartes had discovered around 1636 that the pendulum was not quite isochronous; its period increased somewhat with its amplitude.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Huygens analyzed this problem by determining what curve an object must follow to descend by gravity to the same point in the same time interval, regardless of starting point; the so-called *tautochrone curve*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] By a complicated method that was an early use of calculus, he showed this curve was a cycloid, rather than the circular arc of a pendulum, confirming that the pendulum was not isochronous and Galileo's observation of isochronism was accurate only for small swings.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Huygens also solved the problem of how to calculate the period of an arbitrarily shaped pendulum (called a *compound pendulum*), discovering the *center of oscillation*, and its interchangeability with the pivot point.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The existing clock movement, the verge escapement, made pendulums swing in very wide arcs of about 100°.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Huygens showed this was a source of inaccuracy, causing the period to vary with amplitude changes caused by small unavoidable variations in the clock's drive force.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] To make its period isochronous, Huygens mounted cycloidal-shaped metal guides next to the pivots in his clocks, that constrained the suspension cord and forced the pendulum to follow a cycloid arc (see cycloidal pendulum).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This solution didn't prove as practical as simply limiting the pendulum's swing to small angles of a few degrees.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The realization that only small swings were isochronous motivated the development of the anchor escapement around 1670, which reduced the pendulum swing in clocks to 4°–6°.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This became the standard escapement used in pendulum clocks.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] During the 18th and 19th century, the pendulum clock's role as the most accurate timekeeper motivated much practical research into improving pendulums.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] It was found that a major source of error was that the pendulum rod expanded and contracted with changes in ambient temperature, changing the period of swing.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This was solved with the invention of temperature compensated pendulums, the mercury pendulum in 1721 and the gridiron pendulum in 1726, reducing errors in precision pendulum clocks to a few seconds per week.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The accuracy of gravity measurements made with pendulums was limited by the difficulty of finding the location of their center of oscillation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Huygens had discovered in 1673 that a pendulum has the same period when hung from its center of oscillation as when hung from its pivot, and the distance between the two points was equal to the length of a simple gravity pendulum of the same period.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In 1818 British Captain Henry Kater invented the reversible Kater's pendulum which used this principle, making possible very accurate measurements of gravity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] For the next century the reversible pendulum was the standard method of measuring absolute gravitational acceleration.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In 1851, Jean Bernard Léon Foucault showed that the plane of oscillation of a pendulum, like a gyroscope, tends to stay constant regardless of the motion of the pivot, and that this could be used to demonstrate the rotation of the Earth.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] He suspended a pendulum free to swing in two dimensions (later named the Foucault pendulum) from the dome of the Panthéon in Paris.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The length of the cord was 67 m (220 ft).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Once the pendulum was set in motion, the plane of swing was observed to precess or rotate 360° clockwise in about 32 hours.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This was the first demonstration of the Earth's rotation that did not depend on celestial observations, and a "pendulum mania" broke out, as Foucault pendulums were displayed in many cities and attracted large crowds.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Around 1900 low-thermal-expansion materials began to be used for pendulum rods in the highest precision clocks and other instruments, first invar, a nickel steel alloy, and later fused quartz, which made temperature compensation trivial.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Precision pendulums were housed in low pressure tanks, which kept the air pressure constant to prevent changes in the period due to changes in buoyancy of the pendulum due to changing atmospheric pressure.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The best pendulum clocks achieved accuracy of around a second per year.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The timekeeping accuracy of the pendulum was exceeded by the quartz crystal oscillator, invented in 1921, and quartz clocks, invented in 1927, replaced pendulum clocks as the world's best timekeepers.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Pendulum clocks were used as time standards until World War 2, although the French Time Service continued using them in their official time standard ensemble until 1954.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Pendulum gravimeters were superseded by "free fall" gravimeters in the 1950s, but pendulum instruments continued to be used into the 1970s.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] For 300 years, from its discovery around 1582 until development of the quartz clock in the 1930s, the pendulum was the world's standard for accurate timekeeping.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In addition to clock pendulums, freeswinging seconds pendulums were widely used as precision timers in scientific experiments in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Pendulums require great mechanical stability: a length change of only 0.02%, 0.2 mm in a grandfather clock pendulum, will cause an error of a minute per week.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Pendulums in clocks (see example at right) are usually made of a weight or bob *(b)* suspended by a rod of wood or metal *(a)*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] To reduce air resistance (which accounts for most of the energy loss in precision clocks) the bob is traditionally a smooth disk with a lens-shaped cross section, although in antique clocks it often had carvings or decorations specific to the type of clock.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In quality clocks the bob is made as heavy as the suspension can support and the movement can drive, since this improves the regulation of the clock (see Accuracy below).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] A common weight for seconds pendulum bobs is 15 pounds (6.8 kg).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Instead of hanging from a pivot, clock pendulums are usually supported by a short straight spring *(d)* of flexible metal ribbon.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This avoids the friction and 'play' caused by a pivot, and the slight bending force of the spring merely adds to the pendulum's restoring force.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The highest precision clocks have pivots of 'knife' blades resting on agate plates.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The impulses to keep the pendulum swinging are provided by an arm hanging behind the pendulum called the *crutch*, *(e)*, which ends in a *fork*, *(f)* whose prongs embrace the pendulum rod.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The crutch is pushed back and forth by the clock's escapement, *(g,h)*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Each time the pendulum swings through its centre position, it releases one tooth of the *escape wheel* *(g)*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The force of the clock's mainspring or a driving weight hanging from a pulley, transmitted through the clock's gear train, causes the wheel to turn, and a tooth presses against one of the pallets *(h)*, giving the pendulum a short push.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The clock's wheels, geared to the escape wheel, move forward a fixed amount with each pendulum swing, advancing the clock's hands at a steady rate.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The pendulum always has a means of adjusting the period, usually by an adjustment nut *(c)* under the bob which moves it up or down on the rod.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Moving the bob up decreases the pendulum's length, causing the pendulum to swing faster and the clock to gain time.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Some precision clocks have a small auxiliary adjustment weight on a threaded shaft on the bob, to allow finer adjustment.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Some tower clocks and precision clocks use a tray attached near to the midpoint of the pendulum rod, to which small weights can be added or removed.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This effectively shifts the centre of oscillation and allows the rate to be adjusted without stopping the clock.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The pendulum must be suspended from a rigid support.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] During operation, any elasticity will allow tiny imperceptible swaying motions of the support, which disturbs the clock's period, resulting in error.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Pendulum clocks should be attached firmly to a sturdy wall.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The most common pendulum length in quality clocks, which is always used in grandfather clocks, is the seconds pendulum, about 1 metre (39 inches) long.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In mantel clocks, half-second pendulums, 25 cm (9.8 in) long, or shorter, are used.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Only a few large tower clocks use longer pendulums, the 1.5 second pendulum, 2.25 m (7.4 ft) long, or occasionally the two-second pendulum, 4 m (13 ft) which is used in Big Ben.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The largest source of error in early pendulums was slight changes in length due to thermal expansion and contraction of the pendulum rod with changes in ambient temperature.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This was discovered when people noticed that pendulum clocks ran slower in summer, by as much as a minute per week (one of the first was Godefroy Wendelin, as reported by Huygens in 1658).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Thermal expansion of pendulum rods was first studied by Jean Picard in 1669.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] A pendulum with a steel rod will expand by about 11.3 parts per million (ppm) with each degree Celsius increase, causing it to lose about 0.27 seconds per day for every degree Celsius increase in temperature, or 9 seconds per day for a 33 °C (59 °F) change.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Wood rods expand less, losing only about 6 seconds per day for a 33 °C (59 °F) change, which is why quality clocks often had wooden pendulum rods.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The wood had to be varnished to prevent water vapor from getting in, because changes in humidity also affected the length.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The first device to compensate for this error was the mercury pendulum, invented by George Graham in 1721.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The liquid metal mercury expands in volume with temperature.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In a mercury pendulum, the pendulum's weight (bob) is a container of mercury.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] With a temperature rise, the pendulum rod gets longer, but the mercury also expands and its surface level rises slightly in the container, moving its centre of mass closer to the pendulum pivot.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] By using the correct height of mercury in the container these two effects will cancel, leaving the pendulum's centre of mass, and its period, unchanged with temperature.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Its main disadvantage was that when the temperature changed, the rod would come to the new temperature quickly but the mass of mercury might take a day or two to reach the new temperature, causing the rate to deviate during that time.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] To improve thermal accommodation several thin containers were often used, made of metal.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Mercury pendulums were the standard used in precision regulator clocks into the 20th century.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The most widely used compensated pendulum was the gridiron pendulum, invented in 1726 by John Harrison.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This consists of alternating rods of two different metals, one with lower thermal expansion (CTE), steel, and one with higher thermal expansion, zinc or brass.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The rods are connected by a frame, as shown in the drawing at the right, so that an increase in length of the zinc rods pushes the bob up, shortening the pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] With a temperature increase, the low expansion steel rods make the pendulum longer, while the high expansion zinc rods make it shorter.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] By making the rods of the correct lengths, the greater expansion of the zinc cancels out the expansion of the steel rods which have a greater combined length, and the pendulum stays the same length with temperature.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Zinc-steel gridiron pendulums are made with 5 rods, but the thermal expansion of brass is closer to steel, so brass-steel gridirons usually require 9 rods.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Gridiron pendulums adjust to temperature changes faster than mercury pendulums, but scientists found that friction of the rods sliding in their holes in the frame caused gridiron pendulums to adjust in a series of tiny jumps.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In high precision clocks this caused the clock's rate to change suddenly with each jump.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Later it was found that zinc is subject to creep.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] For these reasons mercury pendulums were used in the highest precision clocks, but gridirons were used in quality regulator clocks.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Gridiron pendulums became so associated with good quality that, to this day, many ordinary clock pendulums have decorative 'fake' gridirons that don't actually have any temperature compensation function.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Around 1900, low thermal expansion materials were developed which could be used as pendulum rods in order to make elaborate temperature compensation unnecessary.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] These were only used in a few of the highest precision clocks before the pendulum became obsolete as a time standard.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In 1896 Charles Édouard Guillaume invented the nickel steel alloy Invar.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Invar pendulums were first used in 1898 in the Riefler regulator clock which achieved accuracy of 15 milliseconds per day.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Suspension springs of Elinvar were used to eliminate temperature variation of the spring's restoring force on the pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Later fused quartz was used which had even lower CTE.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] These materials are the choice for modern high accuracy pendulums.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Increases in barometric pressure increase a pendulum's period slightly due to the first two effects, by about 0.11 seconds per day per kilopascal (0.37 seconds per day per inch of mercury; 0.015 seconds per day per torr).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Researchers using pendulums to measure the acceleration of gravity had to correct the period for the air pressure at the altitude of measurement, computing the equivalent period of a pendulum swinging in vacuum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] A pendulum clock was first operated in a constant-pressure tank by Friedrich Tiede in 1865 at the Berlin Observatory, and by 1900 the highest precision clocks were mounted in tanks that were kept at a constant pressure to eliminate changes in atmospheric pressure.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Alternatively, in some a small aneroid barometer mechanism attached to the pendulum compensated for this effect.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Pendulums are affected by changes in gravitational acceleration, which varies by as much as 0.5% at different locations on Earth, so precision pendulum clocks have to be recalibrated after a move.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Even moving a pendulum clock to the top of a tall building can cause it to lose measurable time from the reduction in gravity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The timekeeping elements in all clocks, which include pendulums, balance wheels, the quartz crystals used in quartz watches, and even the vibrating atoms in atomic clocks, are in physics called harmonic oscillators.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The reason harmonic oscillators are used in clocks is that they vibrate or oscillate at a specific resonant frequency or period and resist oscillating at other rates.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] However, the resonant frequency is not infinitely 'sharp'.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Around the resonant frequency there is a narrow natural band of frequencies (or periods), called the resonance width or bandwidth, where the harmonic oscillator will oscillate.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In a clock, the actual frequency of the pendulum may vary randomly within this resonance width in response to disturbances, but at frequencies outside this band, the clock will not function at all.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The resonance width is determined by the damping, the frictional energy loss per swing of the pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The measure of a harmonic oscillator's resistance to disturbances to its oscillation period is a dimensionless parameter called the *Q* factor equal to the resonant frequency divided by the resonance width.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The higher the *Q*, the smaller the resonance width, and the more constant the frequency or period of the oscillator for a given disturbance.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The reciprocal of the Q is roughly proportional to the limiting accuracy achievable by a harmonic oscillator as a time standard.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The *Q* is related to how long it takes for the oscillations of an oscillator to die out.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The *Q* of a pendulum can be measured by counting the number of oscillations it takes for the amplitude of the pendulum's swing to decay to 1/*e* = 36.8% of its initial swing, and multiplying by *π*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In a clock, the pendulum must receive pushes from the clock's movement to keep it swinging, to replace the energy the pendulum loses to friction.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] These pushes, applied by a mechanism called the escapement, are the main source of disturbance to the pendulum's motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The *Q* is equal to 2*π* times the energy stored in the pendulum, divided by the energy lost to friction during each oscillation period, which is the same as the energy added by the escapement each period.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] It can be seen that the smaller the fraction of the pendulum's energy that is lost to friction, the less energy needs to be added, the less the disturbance from the escapement, the more 'independent' the pendulum is of the clock's mechanism, and the more constant its period is.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The *Q* of a pendulum is given by: $Q={\frac {M\omega }{\Gamma }}$ where *M* is the mass of the bob, *ω* = 2*π*/*T* is the pendulum's radian frequency of oscillation, and Γ is the frictional damping force on the pendulum per unit velocity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The *Q* of pendulums ranges from several thousand in an ordinary clock to several hundred thousand for precision regulator pendulums swinging in vacuum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] A quality home pendulum clock might have a *Q* of 10,000 and an accuracy of 10 seconds per month.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The most accurate commercially produced pendulum clock was the Shortt-Synchronome free pendulum clock, invented in 1921.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Its Invar master pendulum swinging in a vacuum tank had a *Q* of 110,000 and an error rate of around a second per year.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Their Q of 103–105 is one reason why pendulums are more accurate timekeepers than the balance wheels in watches, with *Q* around 100–300, but less accurate than the quartz crystals in quartz clocks, with *Q* of 105–106.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Pendulums (unlike, for example, quartz crystals) have a low enough *Q* that the disturbance caused by the impulses to keep them moving is generally the limiting factor on their timekeeping accuracy.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Therefore, the design of the escapement, the mechanism that provides these impulses, has a large effect on the accuracy of a clock pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] If the impulses given to the pendulum by the escapement each swing could be exactly identical, the response of the pendulum would be identical, and its period would be constant.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] However, this is not achievable; unavoidable random fluctuations in the force due to friction of the clock's pallets, lubrication variations, and changes in the torque provided by the clock's power source as it runs down, mean that the force of the impulse applied by the escapement varies.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] If these variations in the escapement's force cause changes in the pendulum's width of swing (amplitude), this will cause corresponding slight changes in the period, since (as discussed at top) a pendulum with a finite swing is not quite isochronous.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Therefore, the goal of traditional escapement design is to apply the force with the proper profile, and at the correct point in the pendulum's cycle, so force variations have no effect on the pendulum's amplitude.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] This is called an *isochronous escapement*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] Clockmakers had known for centuries that the disturbing effect of the escapement's drive force on the period of a pendulum is smallest if given as a short impulse as the pendulum passes through its bottom equilibrium position.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] If the impulse occurs before the pendulum reaches bottom, during the downward swing, it will have the effect of shortening the pendulum's natural period, so an increase in drive force will decrease the period.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] If the impulse occurs after the pendulum reaches bottom, during the upswing, it will lengthen the period, so an increase in drive force will increase the pendulum's period.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] In 1826 British astronomer George Airy proved this; specifically, he proved that if a pendulum is driven by an impulse that is symmetrical about its bottom equilibrium position, the pendulum's period will be unaffected by changes in the drive force.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p01] The most accurate escapements, such as the deadbeat, approximately satisfy this condition.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The presence of the acceleration of gravity *g* in the periodicity equation (1) for a pendulum means that the local gravitational acceleration of the Earth can be calculated from the period of a pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] A pendulum can therefore be used as a gravimeter to measure the local gravity, which varies by over 0.5% across the surface of the Earth.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The pendulum in a clock is disturbed by the pushes it receives from the clock movement, so freeswinging pendulums were used, and were the standard instruments of gravimetry up to the 1930s.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The difference between clock pendulums and gravimeter pendulums is that to measure gravity, the pendulum's length as well as its period has to be measured.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The period of freeswinging pendulums could be found to great precision by comparing their swing with a precision clock that had been adjusted to keep correct time by the passage of stars overhead.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In the early measurements, a weight on a cord was suspended in front of the clock pendulum, and its length adjusted until the two pendulums swung in exact synchronism.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Then the length of the cord was measured.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] From the length and the period, *g* could be calculated from equation (1).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The seconds pendulum, a pendulum with a period of two seconds so each swing takes one second, was widely used to measure gravity, because its period could be easily measured by comparing it to precision regulator clocks, which all had seconds pendulums.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] By the late 17th century, the length of the seconds pendulum became the standard measure of the strength of gravitational acceleration at a location.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] By 1700 its length had been measured with submillimeter accuracy at several cities in Europe.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The precision of the early gravity measurements above was limited by the difficulty of measuring the length of the pendulum, *L*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] *L* was the length of an idealized simple gravity pendulum (described at top), which has all its mass concentrated in a point at the end of the cord.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] But there was no accurate way of determining the center of oscillation in a real pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Huygens's discovery is sometimes referred to as *Huygens's law of the (cycloidal) pendulum*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] To get around this problem, the early researchers above approximated an ideal simple pendulum as closely as possible by using a metal sphere suspended by a light wire or cord.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] If the wire was light enough, the center of oscillation was close to the center of gravity of the ball, at its geometric center.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] This "ball and wire" type of pendulum wasn't very accurate, because it didn't swing as a rigid body, and the elasticity of the wire caused its length to change slightly as the pendulum swung.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] However Huygens had also proved that in any pendulum, the pivot point and the center of oscillation were interchangeable.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] That is, if a pendulum were turned upside down and hung from its center of oscillation, it would have the same period as it did in the previous position, and the old pivot point would be the new center of oscillation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] British physicist and army captain Henry Kater in 1817 realized that Huygens's principle could be used to find the length of a simple pendulum with the same period as a real pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Kater built a reversible pendulum (*see drawing*) consisting of a brass bar with two opposing pivots made of short triangular "knife" blades *(a)* near either end.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] It could be swung from either pivot, with the knife blades supported on agate plates.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Rather than make one pivot adjustable, he attached the pivots a meter apart and instead adjusted the periods with a moveable weight on the pendulum rod *(b,c)*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In operation, the pendulum is hung in front of a precision clock, and the period timed, then turned upside down and the period timed again.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The weight is adjusted with the adjustment screw until the periods are equal.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Then putting this period and the distance between the pivots into equation (1) gives the gravitational acceleration *g* very accurately.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Kater timed the swing of his pendulum using the "*method of coincidences*" and measured the distance between the two pivots with a micrometer.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] After applying corrections for the finite amplitude of swing, the buoyancy of the bob, the barometric pressure and altitude, and temperature, he obtained a value of 39.13929 inches for the seconds pendulum at London, in vacuum, at sea level, at 62 °F.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The largest variation from the mean of his 12 observations was 0.00028 in. representing a precision of gravity measurement of 7×10−6 (7 mGal or 70 μm/s2).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Kater's measurement was used as Britain's official standard of length (see below) from 1824 to 1855.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Reversible pendulums (known technically as "convertible" pendulums) employing Kater's principle were used for absolute gravity measurements into the 1930s.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The increased accuracy made possible by Kater's pendulum helped make gravimetry a standard part of geodesy.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Since the exact location (latitude and longitude) of the 'station' where the gravity measurement was made was necessary, gravity measurements became part of surveying, and pendulums were taken on the great geodetic surveys of the 18th century, particularly the Great Trigonometric Survey of India.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Relative pendulum gravimeters were superseded by the simpler LaCoste zero-length spring gravimeter, invented in 1934 by Lucien LaCoste.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Absolute (reversible) pendulum gravimeters were replaced in the 1950s by free fall gravimeters, in which a weight is allowed to fall in a vacuum tank and its acceleration is measured by an optical interferometer.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Because the acceleration of gravity is constant at a given point on Earth, the period of a simple pendulum at a given location depends only on its length.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Additionally, gravity varies only slightly at different locations.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Almost from the pendulum's discovery until the early 19th century, this property led scientists to suggest using a pendulum of a given period as a standard of length.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Until the 19th century, countries based their systems of length measurement on prototypes, metal bar primary standards, such as the standard yard in Britain kept at the Houses of Parliament, and the standard *toise* in France, kept at Paris.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] These were vulnerable to damage or destruction over the years, and because of the difficulty of comparing prototypes, the same unit often had different lengths in distant towns, creating opportunities for fraud.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] During the Enlightenment scientists argued for a length standard that was based on some property of nature that could be determined by measurement, creating an indestructible, universal standard.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The period of pendulums could be measured very precisely by timing them with clocks that were set by the stars.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] A pendulum standard amounted to defining the unit of length by the gravitational force of the Earth, for all intents constant, and the second, which was defined by the rotation rate of the Earth, also constant.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The idea was that anyone, anywhere on Earth, could recreate the standard by constructing a pendulum that swung with the defined period and measuring its length.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Virtually all proposals were based on the seconds pendulum, in which each swing (a half period) takes one second, which is about a meter (39 inches) long, because by the late 17th century it had become a standard for measuring gravity (see previous section).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] By the 18th century its length had been measured with sub-millimeter accuracy at a number of cities in Europe and around the world.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The initial attraction of the pendulum length standard was that it was believed (by early scientists such as Huygens and Wren) that gravity was constant over the Earth's surface, so a given pendulum had the same period at any point on Earth.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] So the length of the standard pendulum could be measured at any location, and would not be tied to any given nation or region; it would be a truly democratic, worldwide standard.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Although Richer found in 1672 that gravity varies at different points on the globe, the idea of a pendulum length standard remained popular, because it was found that gravity only varies with latitude.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Gravitational acceleration increases smoothly from the equator to the poles, due to the oblate shape of the Earth, so at any given latitude (east–west line), gravity was constant enough that the length of a seconds pendulum was the same within the measurement capability of the 18th century.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Thus the unit of length could be defined at a given latitude and measured at any point along that latitude.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] For example, a pendulum standard defined at 45° north latitude, a popular choice, could be measured in parts of France, Italy, Croatia, Serbia, Romania, Russia, Kazakhstan, China, Mongolia, the United States and Canada.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In addition, it could be recreated at any location at which the gravitational acceleration had been accurately measured.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] By the mid-19th century, increasingly accurate pendulum measurements by Edward Sabine and Thomas Young revealed that gravity, and thus the length of any pendulum standard, varied measurably with local geologic features such as mountains and dense subsurface rocks.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] So a pendulum length standard had to be defined at a single point on Earth and could only be measured there.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] This took much of the appeal from the concept, and efforts to adopt pendulum standards were abandoned.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] One of the first to suggest defining length with a pendulum was Flemish scientist Isaac Beeckman who in 1631 recommended making the seconds pendulum "the invariable measure for all people at all times in all places".
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Marin Mersenne, who first measured the seconds pendulum in 1644, also suggested it.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The first official proposal for a pendulum standard was made by the British Royal Society in 1660, advocated by Christiaan Huygens and Ole Rømer, basing it on Mersenne's work, and Huygens in *Horologium Oscillatorium* proposed a "horary foot" defined as 1/3 of the seconds pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Christopher Wren was another early supporter.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In 1671 Jean Picard proposed a pendulum-defined 'universal foot' in his influential *Mesure de la Terre*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Gabriel Mouton around 1670 suggested defining the *toise* either by a seconds pendulum or a minute of terrestrial degree.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] A plan for a complete system of units based on the pendulum was advanced in 1675 by Italian polymath Tito Livio Burratini.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In France in 1747, geographer Charles Marie de la Condamine proposed defining length by a seconds pendulum at the equator; since at this location a pendulum's swing wouldn't be distorted by the Earth's rotation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] James Steuart (1780) and George Skene Keith were also supporters.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] By the end of the 18th century, when many nations were reforming their weight and measure systems, the seconds pendulum was the leading choice for a new definition of length, advocated by prominent scientists in several major nations.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In 1790, then US Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson proposed to Congress a comprehensive decimalized US 'metric system' based on the seconds pendulum at 38° North latitude, the mean latitude of the United States.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In Britain the leading advocate of the pendulum was politician John Riggs Miller.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] When his efforts to promote a joint British–French–American metric system fell through in 1790, he proposed a British system based on the length of the seconds pendulum at London.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] This standard was adopted in 1824 (below).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In the discussions leading up to the French adoption of the metric system in 1791, the leading candidate for the definition of the new unit of length, the metre, was the seconds pendulum at 45° North latitude.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] It was advocated by a group led by French politician Talleyrand and mathematician Antoine Nicolas Caritat de Condorcet.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] This was one of the three final options considered by the French Academy of Sciences committee.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] However, on March 19, 1791, the committee instead chose to base the metre on the length of the meridian through Paris.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] A pendulum definition was rejected because of its variability at different locations, and because it defined length by a unit of time.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] (However, since 1983 the metre has been officially defined in terms of the length of the second and the speed of light.) A possible additional reason is that the radical French Academy didn't want to base their new system on the second, a traditional and nondecimal unit from the *ancien regime*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Although not defined by the pendulum, the final length chosen for the metre, 10−7 of the pole-to-equator meridian arc, was very close to the length of the seconds pendulum (0.9937 m), within 0.63%.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Although no reason for this particular choice was given at the time, it was probably to facilitate the use of the seconds pendulum as a secondary standard, as was proposed in the official document.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] So the modern world's standard unit of length is certainly closely linked historically with the seconds pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Britain and Denmark appear to be the only nations that (for a short time) based their units of length on the pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In 1821 the Danish inch was defined as 1/38 of the length of the mean solar seconds pendulum at 45° latitude at the meridian of Skagen, at sea level, in vacuum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] This also became the US standard, since at the time the US used British measures.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] However, when the prototype yard was lost in the 1834 Houses of Parliament fire, it proved impossible to recreate it accurately from the pendulum definition, and in 1855 Britain repealed the pendulum standard and returned to prototype standards.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] A pendulum in which the rod is not vertical but almost horizontal was used in early seismometers for measuring Earth tremors.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The bob of the pendulum does not move when its mounting does, and the difference in the movements is recorded on a drum chart.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] This principle, called Schuler tuning, is used in inertial guidance systems in ships and aircraft that operate on the surface of the Earth.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] No physical pendulum is used, but the control system that keeps the inertial platform containing the gyroscopes stable is modified so the device acts as though it is attached to such a pendulum, keeping the platform always facing down as the vehicle moves on the curved surface of the Earth.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In 1665 Huygens made a curious observation about pendulum clocks.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Two clocks had been placed on his mantlepiece, and he noted that they had acquired an opposing motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] That is, their pendulums were beating in unison but in the opposite direction; 180° out of phase.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Regardless of how the two clocks were started, he found that they would eventually return to this state, thus making the first recorded observation of a coupled oscillator.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The cause of this behavior was that the two pendulums were affecting each other through slight motions of the supporting mantlepiece.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] This process is called entrainment or mode locking in physics and is observed in other coupled oscillators.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Synchronized pendulums have been used in clocks and were widely used in gravimeters in the early 20th century.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Although Huygens only observed out-of-phase synchronization, recent investigations have shown the existence of in-phase synchronization, as well as "death" states wherein one or both clocks stops.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Pendulum motion appears in religious ceremonies as well.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The swinging incense burner called a censer, also known as a thurible, is an example of a pendulum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Pendulums are also seen at many gatherings in eastern Mexico where they mark the turning of the tides on the day which the tides are at their highest point.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Pendulums are widely used in science education as an example of a harmonic oscillator, to teach dynamics and oscillatory motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] One use is to demonstrate the law of conservation of energy.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] A heavy object such as a bowling ball or wrecking ball is attached to a string.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The weight is then moved to within a few inches of a volunteer's face, then released and allowed to swing and come back.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] In most instances, the weight reverses direction and then returns to (almost) the same position as the original release location — *i.e.* a small distance from the volunteer's face — thus leaving the volunteer unharmed.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] On occasion the volunteer is injured if either the volunteer does not stand still or the pendulum is initially released with a push (so that when it returns it surpasses the release position).
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Another demonstration is the pendulum wave.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] It is claimed that the pendulum was used as an instrument of torture and execution by the Spanish Inquisition in the 18th century.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The allegation is contained in the 1826 book *The history of the Inquisition of Spain* by the Spanish priest, historian and liberal activist Juan Antonio Llorente.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] A swinging pendulum whose edge is a knife blade slowly descends toward a bound prisoner until it cuts into his body.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] This method of torture came to popular consciousness through the 1842 short story "The Pit and the Pendulum" by American author Edgar Allan Poe.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Most knowledgeable sources are skeptical that this torture was ever actually used.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] The only evidence of its use is one paragraph in the preface to Llorente's 1826 *History*, relating a second-hand account by a single prisoner released from the Inquisition's Madrid dungeon in 1820, who purportedly described the pendulum torture method.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Modern sources point out that due to Jesus' admonition against bloodshed, Inquisitors were only allowed to use torture methods which did not spill blood, and the pendulum method would have violated this stricture.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] One theory is that Llorente misunderstood the account he heard; the prisoner was actually referring to another common Inquisition torture, the *strappado* (garrucha), in which the prisoner has his hands tied behind his back and is hoisted off the floor by a rope tied to his hands.
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] This method was also known as the "pendulum".
[src:oscillations-resonance/pendulum-p02] Poe's popular horror tale, and public awareness of the Inquisition's other brutal methods, has kept the myth of this elaborate torture method alive.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] It results in an oscillation that is described by a sinusoid which continues indefinitely (if uninhibited by friction or any other dissipation of energy).
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Simple harmonic motion can serve as a mathematical model for a variety of motions, but is typified by the oscillation of a mass on a spring when it is subject to the linear elastic restoring force given by Hooke's law.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] The motion is sinusoidal in time and demonstrates a single resonant frequency.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Simple harmonic motion can also be used to model molecular vibration.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Simple harmonic motion provides a basis for the characterization of more complicated periodic motion through the techniques of Fourier analysis.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] The motion of a particle moving along a straight line with an acceleration whose direction is always toward a fixed point on the line and whose magnitude is proportional to the displacement from the fixed point is called simple harmonic motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] In the diagram, a simple harmonic oscillator, consisting of a weight attached to one end of a spring, is shown.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] The other end of the spring is connected to a rigid support such as a wall.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] If the system is left at rest at the equilibrium position then there is no net force acting on the mass.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] However, if the mass is displaced from the equilibrium position, the spring exerts a restoring elastic force that obeys Hooke's law.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Mathematically, $\mathbf {F} =-k\mathbf {x} ,$ where **F** is the restoring elastic force exerted by the spring (in SI units: N), *k* is the spring constant (N·m−1), and **x** is the displacement from the equilibrium position (in metres).
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Once the mass is displaced from its equilibrium position, it experiences a net restoring force.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] As a result, it accelerates and starts going back to the equilibrium position.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] When the mass moves closer to the equilibrium position, the restoring force decreases.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] At the equilibrium position, the net restoring force vanishes.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] However, at *x* = 0, the mass has momentum because of the acceleration that the restoring force has imparted.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Therefore, the mass continues past the equilibrium position, compressing the spring.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] A net restoring force then slows it down until its velocity reaches zero, whereupon it is accelerated back to the equilibrium position again.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] As long as the system has no energy loss, the mass continues to oscillate.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Thus simple harmonic motion is a type of periodic motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] If energy is lost in the system, then the mass exhibits damped oscillation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Note if the real space and phase space plot are not co-linear, the phase space motion becomes elliptical.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] The area enclosed depends on the amplitude and the maximum momentum.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] In Newtonian mechanics, for one-dimensional simple harmonic motion, the equation of motion, which is a second-order linear ordinary differential equation with **constant** coefficients, can be obtained by means of Newton's second law and Hooke's law for a mass on a spring.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] $F_{\mathrm {net} }=m{\frac {\mathrm {d} ^{2}x}{\mathrm {d} t^{2}}}=-kx,$ where m is the inertial mass of the oscillating body, x is its displacement from the equilibrium (or mean) position, and *k* is a constant (the spring constant for a mass on a spring).
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] In the solution, *c*1 and *c*2 are two constants determined by the initial conditions (specifically, the initial position at time *t* = 0 is *c*1, while the initial velocity is *c*2*ω*), and the origin is set to be the equilibrium position.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Each of these constants carries a physical meaning of the motion: *A* is the amplitude (maximum displacement from the equilibrium position), *ω* = 2*πf* is the angular frequency, and *φ* is the initial phase.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] These equations demonstrate that the simple harmonic motion is isochronous (the period and frequency are independent of the amplitude and the initial phase of the motion).
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] The following physical systems are some examples of simple harmonic oscillator.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] A mass *m* attached to a spring of spring constant *k* exhibits simple harmonic motion in closed space.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] The equation for describing the period: $T=2\pi {\sqrt {\frac {m}{k}}}$ shows the period of oscillation is independent of the amplitude, though in practice the amplitude should be small.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] The above equation is also valid in the case when an additional constant force is being applied on the mass, i.e. the additional constant force cannot change the period of oscillation.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Simple harmonic motion can be considered the one-dimensional projection of uniform circular motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] If an object moves with angular speed *ω* around a circle of radius *r* centered at the origin of the *xy*-plane, then its motion along each coordinate is simple harmonic motion with amplitude *r* and angular frequency *ω*.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] The motion of a body in which it moves to-and-fro about a definite point is also called oscillatory motion or vibratory motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] The time period is able to be calculated by $T=2\pi {\sqrt {\frac {l}{g}}}$ where *l* is the distance from rotation to the object's center of mass undergoing SHM and *g* is acceleration due to gravity.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] This is analogous to the mass-spring system.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] In the small-angle approximation, the motion of a simple pendulum is approximated by simple harmonic motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] This shows that the period of oscillation is independent of the amplitude and mass of the pendulum but not of the acceleration due to gravity, g , therefore a pendulum of the same length on the Moon would swing more slowly due to the Moon's lower gravitational field strength.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] Because the value of g varies slightly over the surface of the earth, the time period will vary slightly from place to place and will also vary with height above sea level.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] which makes angular acceleration directly proportional and opposite to *θ*, satisfying the definition of simple harmonic motion (that net force is directly proportional to the displacement from the mean position and is directed towards the mean position).
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] A Scotch yoke mechanism can be used to convert between rotational motion and linear reciprocating motion.
[src:oscillations-resonance/simple-harmonic-motion] The linear motion can take various forms depending on the shape of the slot, but the basic yoke with a constant rotation speed produces a linear motion that is simple harmonic in form.
